How to use Bimostitch

You can combine multiple overlapping photos into seamless multi-row panoramas with Bimostitch.

• Press on the gallery icon, select an album and then select two or more photos/images, in any order you like, then press to merge or stitch them.

• For more info on getting great panorama results check tips section.

• You can stitch 2 to 200 photos or more at once with Bimostitch. Though more than 200 might lead to unpredictable results . Bimostitch will automatically find and render all panoramas in the group of selected images.

• Stitching process might take a while depending on your photos resolution, photos richness, number of selected photos and your phones/tablet processing power and memory.

• The resulting panoramas get stored in the panorama album by default. You can then share or edit them.

• While in the panorama gallery use standard Android long press for features such as sharing, editing e.t.c.

• Note: Some features such as sharing and editing might be active or inactive depending on your other installed apps. So, to edit panoramas be sure to have an image editor app installed.

• Use photos from other apps or capture some by yourself with your camera, see tips section for more info on this.

• The output panoramas can be in spherical, cylindrical or rectangular (planar) co-ordinates, you can find this in the settings where there is actually an additional choice, auto-detect, so that the app will automatically choose between the three projection methods.

• All newly generated panoramas will have default names PANO # and placed at the top of the list in the gallery, so be sure to rename them.

• Anti-aliasing filtering moderately blurs the source images prior to rendering and thus the final panorama will look slightly blurred.

• Auto-crop automatically crops panoramas with the largest rectangular area as much as possible. Thus it minimises reduction in overall panorama resolution. Manual cropping is harder to do and most cropping apps will drastically reduce the panorama resolution unnecessarily.

• The advanced blending feature tries to eliminate double images effect due to small image registration errors, thus this results in much better looking panoramas but comes at a price of computational resources.

• Voronoi blending is just a bonus feature for artistic reasons.

• Preview mode is for those who which to have more control over the output results.

• Did you know BIMO stands for BIologically MOtivated.

• More importantly have fun with Bimostitch and stay cool.

THANK YOU.

Tips for stitching better panoramas

The following guidelines will help you make the best possible panoramas with Bimostitch.

• Ensure that there are no duplicate photos in your selection before starting the stitch process.

• Do not use completely featureless photos such as photos containing only clear plain blue sky, Bimostitch might ignore them.

• Try turning on/off autostraightening in the settings. Turn it on if the panoramas are not straight, especially for a full 360 degree panorama. Turn it off if the rendering is poor, like the panorama appears compressed to one side.

When capturing your own photos for stitching:

• Avoid capturing plain clear photos.

• Avoid too many repeated or very similar looking structures in overlapping photos, this can lead to false matches.

• Make sure to hold your phone firmly in landscape or portrait mode and rotate it such that the camera lens should be the rotation axis. Rotate the camera in any direction but keep the camera lens on the same point as much as possible. Rotate your phone slowly and stay still when snapping to avoid motion blur. Do not use your body as a rotation axis.

• Ensure you capture images with not less than 25% overlap for better results.

• Avoid taking pictures with significantly different lighting conditions and avoid taking pictures in direct sunlight.

• Make sure there are no moving objects where images overlap.

• Stitch images in groups of not more than 50 images at once for better results. And ensure your phone/tablet has enough memory/RAM for larger image sets.

• Use your favourite camera apps for taking photos.

• Make sure the captured photos are placed in your systems photo gallery.

• Turn on anti-aliasing filter in the settings menu for much better looking panoramas.

• Turn on auto-crop for panoramas with even rectangular borders instead of wavy irregular ones, auto-crop will crop the panorama with minimal reduction in resolution during rendering thus is a convenient option to turn on.

• Auto-exposure balancing tries to balance out the exposure differences in photos so that the panorama looks uniform, it is recommended to turn this feature on, but turn it off if the result is too bright.

• There are three projections spherical, cylindrical and planar and a convenient auto-detect feature so that you need not worry about which projection method will work best, thus it is recommended to select auto-detect.

• For a quick way to check different settings before final rendering make sure to turn on preview mode in the settings.

• You can also turn on auto-delete feature for camera captured photos so that the app can delete the captured photos after stitching is complete.

• As much as possible turn on all the features for a better overall experience.

• More importantly have fun with Bimostitch and stay cool.
